Let $r,s,t$ in the set of complex numbers be the roots of the equation $$2x^3-3x^2+4x-1=0$$</think> <answer>As you know, in cubic equations, if $r+v,s+v,t+v$ are the roots of the equation $$x^3-px^2+qx-r=0,$$ then $r+s+t=3v$ and $rs+st+tr=p-(1+v^2)$. So, $$r+s+t=\frac{3}{2}\qquad rs+st+tr=-\frac{1}{2}.$$
Using these facts, we can express $r^2+s^2+t^2$ as follows:
\begin{align*}
r^2+s^2+t^2&=(r+s+t)^2-2(r+s+t)(rs+st+tr)-2rst\\
&=(2)(\frac{3}{2})^2-2(\frac{3}{2})(-\frac{1}{2})-2\cdot\frac{1}{3}\\
&=\frac{5}{2}.
\end{align*}
Here is an alternative and simpler way. By Vieta's formula, if $p(x)=x^3-ax^2+bx-1$ and $r+s+t=3$, then 
$$r^2+s^2+t^2= (r+s+t)^3-3(r+s+t)(rs+st+tr)+3rtr.$$
But we know that if $r$ and $t$ are roots of $p(x)$, then $r+t=3-s$ and $rt=\color{red}{\frac{b-1}{6}}$. Since $p(x)=0$ for both $r,t$,
\begin{align*}
p_r:r^4-3r^3+br^2-2r^2+ar-r-1&=0\\r^2(s-r)+(rs+b+s-3)r+s^2+as-s-1&=0\\ r^2(3-r)+(rs+b+s-3)r+s^2+as-s-1&=0\\3r+r^2(s-r)+(rs+b+s-3)r+s^2+as-s-1&=0
\end{align*}
which simplifies to
$$\begin{align*}
